      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The concept of \"colorblindness\" is often rooted in the belief that acknowledging race creates artificial barriers to true meritocracy, suggesting that individuals should be judged solely on their inherent talents and efforts regardless of their background. Proponents argue that any policy explicitly considering race, such as affirmative action, disrupts the natural flow of competition and rewards group identity over individual achievement, which they view as a fundamental violation of fairness. From this perspective, the logic holds that if everyone is treated identically by the rules, the resulting outcomes are the most accurate reflection of who is truly capable, and any special treatment is seen as an unfair advantage that devalues the hard work of those who succeed without it. Ultimately, this viewpoint posits that diversity initiatives can inadvertently lower standards or create resentment by prioritizing representation numbers over the pure, unadulterated excellence of the individual candidate.",
